sh and French Canadian nationalism, but the nature of that contact, as Gordon shows, had profound limitations. The Hero and the Historians is necessary reading for anyone interested in the underlying culture of national identity � and national unity � in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481743140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774817431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774817431/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles